<section xml:id="sec_fourth-circular" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Circular Motion</title>
  
   <introduction>
    <p>
      Please read circular kinamatics before learning details here. <xref ref="subsec-cir_kinem"/> 
      Uniform circular motion is the motion of an object moving at a constant speed 
      on a circular path. For an object to be in uniform circular motion, 
      there must be a net force acting on it. 
      <me>
        \sum F_{r}  =  m a_{r} = \frac{mv^{2}}{r}
      </me>
     this is a radial-component of force.
<me>
  \sum F_{t}  =  m a_{t} = mr\alpha
</me>
 this is a tangential-component of force.
 <me>
  v  =  r\omega = 2\pi r f;  \quad f  = \frac{1}{T} 
 </me>
 If the centripetal force vanishes, the object flies off at a tangent to the circle.
    </p>
   </introduction>

   <subsection xml:id="subsec-con_pendulum">
    <title>Horizontal Circle </title>
    <p>
      <idx><h>Horizontal Circle </h></idx> Horizontal Circle or a A conical pendulum is 
      mass attached to a weightless and inextensible string over the rigid support 
      and moves in a horizontal circle. Let us consider a body of mass, <m>m</m> tied 
      with the string of length, <m>l</m> over the rigid support <m>O</m> and whirl in 
      a horizontal circle of radius, <m>r</m>. At any instant of time the body 
      is at <m>P</m> where the  tension, <m>T</m> is acted along the string as shown in <xref ref="horizcir"/>. 
      The vertical component of tension <m>T\cos\theta</m> balances <m>mg</m> and 
      unbalanced the horizontal component <m>T\sin\theta</m>  provides necessary centripetal force. 
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="horizcir">
      <caption></caption>
      <image source="horizcir.png" width="35%"/>
    </figure>
    <p>
      <men xml:id="eqn-horizcir1">
        T\cos\theta=mg 
      </men>
      <men xml:id="eqn-horizcir2">
        T\sin\theta=\frac{mv^{2}}{r} 
      </men>
        Dividing eqn. <xref ref="eqn-horizcir2"/> with <xref ref="eqn-horizcir1"/>, we get -
        <me>
          \tan\theta=\frac{v^{2}}{rg}
        </me>
        <me>
          or, \quad \theta=\tan^{-1}\left(\frac{v^{2}}{rg}\right)
        </me>
        The time period <m>T'</m> can be given by 
        <me>
          T'=\frac{2\pi r}{v}= 2\pi\frac{r}{\sqrt{rg\tan\theta}}=2\pi\sqrt{\frac{r}{g\tan\theta}}
        </me>
        <me>
          = 2\pi\sqrt{\frac{l\sin\theta}{g\tan\theta}}=2\pi\sqrt{\frac{l\cos\theta}{g}}
        </me>
        If  <m>\theta \to 90^{o}</m>, then tension in the string <m>T \to \infty</m>, 
      which is not possible. Hence the body never receives the same height as its fixed support. 
    </p>
   </subsection>

   <subsection xml:id="subsec-vertcir">
    <title>Vertical Circle</title>
    <p>
      <idx><h>verticle circle</h></idx>Consider a body of mass, <m>m</m> attached with a string of length, <m>l</m> 
      and  revolve in the vertical circle of radius, <m>r</m>. At any instant 
      of time the body is at P such that string makes an angle  <m>\theta</m> 
      with the vertical. The weight (mg) of a body is acted downward which 
      can be resolved into two components. One component <m>mg\cos\theta</m> 
      is against tension <m>T</m> in the string and another component <m>mg\sin\theta</m>  
      affect the speed of the body. Because of <m>g\sin\theta</m> body slows down 
      as it goes up and speed up as it comes down. Hence the motion in a vertical 
      circle is not uniform.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="vertcir">
      <caption></caption>
      <image source="vertcir.png" width="35%"/>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The necessary centripetal force in this case is provided by 
      <me>
        T-mg\cos\theta  =\frac{mv^{2}}{r}
      </me>
      <me>
        \therefore T = m\left[\frac{v^{2}}{r}+g\cos\theta\right]
      </me>
    </p>
     <p>
      At <m>\theta =0</m>, 
      <me>
        T= m\left[\frac{v^{2}}{r}+g\right],
      </me>
      lowest point of ride.
     </p>
      <p>
        At  <m>\theta =90^{o}</m>, 
      <me>
        T= m\left[\frac{v^{2}}{r}\right],
      </me>
      quarter point of ride.
      </p>
     <p>
      At  <m>\theta =180^{o}</m>, 
      <me>
        T= m\left[\frac{v^{2}}{r}-g\right],
      </me>
       highest point of ride.
     </p>
       <p>
        For a minimum velocity at the highest point <m>T =0</m>, 
       hence <me>
        \frac{v^{2}}{r}-g=0
       </me>
       <men xml:id="eqn-vertcir1">
       or, \quad v=\sqrt{rg}
       </men>
       </p>
      </subsection>
  </section>

